Jim Hammerand


                            Digital Editor                        

Minneapolis / St. Paul Business Journal









 



 











 Enlarge





                Ellyn Shook will become Accenture's chief human resources officer on March 1.            

                Accenture            








 



Minneapolis executive Ellyn Shook has been promoted to chief human resources officer for Dublin-based consulting firm Accenture.
Shook starts in her new role on March 1, replacing Jill Smart, who has held the position for nine years and will retire at the end of August.













 Enlarge






                            Ellyn Shook will become Accenture's chief human resources officer on March 1.                        
Accenture










 


Shook, 50, joined Accenture in 1988 (view her company bio here). She already heads Accenture's global HR strategies and programs and has responsibility for the company's talent strategy, including career and performance management, employee engagement, retention and total rewards, according to a news release.
RELATED: List Leaders: Largest Twin Cities management consulting firms




She'll now join the company's global management committee, which includes CEO Pierre Nanterme, Chief Financial Officer David Rowland, Chief Operating Officer Joe Deblaere and other C-suite executives. Shook will stay in the Minneapolis office.
Nanterme said in a statement that Shook “has distinguished herself in a number of leadership positions within human resources over her 25-year career, and has played a key role in nearly every major transformation we have made as a company, including designing and implementing our executive compensation strategies and equity programs."
Shook is also on the Women in Business advisory board at the University of Minnesota's Carlson School of Management, and serve on Junior Achievement of the Upper Midwest's board of directors executive committee.
Accenture had about 1,100 consultants in the Twin Cities metro and 220,000 worldwide in July 2013, according to Minneapolis/St. Paul Business Journal research. The total metro employee count as of the end of August was 1,500, Accenture said.
RELATED: Accenture, 2013 MSPBJ Best Places to Work











 







